In 1946 Canadian Airforce pilot McMullen was returning to RAF Goosepool (now{Teesside Airport)}when his plane caught fire. He made his crew bale out and steered the doomed plane away from the town. It crashed near Lingfield Lane which was later renamed {McMullen Road}in his honour.
In{June 1985}the daughter of the pilot came from Canada and unveiled a picture in honour of her father. Formerly, a plaque had been erected near the site of the crash but it had disappeared. At present the Darlington Council are considering a new plaque but are not sure where to place it. {Jonathan Riding}
